# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: real-time-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] With scheduling periodic processes that have deadlines equal to their periods, EDF has a utilization bound of 100%.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] where the $\left\{C_{i}\right\}$ are the worst-case computation-times of the n processes and the $\left\{T_{i}\right\}$ are their respective inter-arrival periods (assumed to be equal to the relative deadlines).
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] That is, EDF can guarantee that all deadlines are met provided that the total CPU utilization is not more than 100%.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Compared to fixed-priority scheduling techniques like rate-monotonic scheduling, EDF can guarantee all the deadlines in the system at higher loading.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Note that use the schedulability test formula under deadline as period.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] When deadline is less than period, things are different.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Here is an example: The four periodic tasks needs scheduling, where each task is depicted as TaskNo( computation time, relative deadline, period).
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] This task group meets utilization is no greater than 1.0, where utilization is calculated as 5/20+3/11+4/10+1/20 = 0.97 (two digits rounded), but is still unschedulable, check **EDF Scheduling Failure** figure for details.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] EDF is also an *optimal* scheduling algorithm on non-preemptive uniprocessors, but only among the class of scheduling algorithms that do not allow inserted idle time.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Where *p* represents the penalty for non-preemption, given by *max* $\left\{C_{i}\right\}$ / *min* $\left\{T_{i}\right\}$ .
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] If this factor can be kept small, non-preemptive EDF can be beneficial as it has low implementation overhead.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] However, when the system is overloaded, the set of processes that will miss deadlines is largely unpredictable (it will be a function of the exact deadlines and time at which the overload occurs.) This is a considerable disadvantage to a real time systems designer.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] The algorithm is also difficult to implement in hardware and there is a tricky issue of representing deadlines in different ranges (deadlines can not be more precise than the granularity of the clock used for the scheduling).
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] If a modular arithmetic is used to calculate future deadlines relative to now, the field storing a future relative deadline must accommodate at least the value of the (("duration" {of the longest expected time to completion} * 2) + "now").
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Therefore EDF is not commonly found in industrial real-time computer systems.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Instead, most real-time computer systems use fixed-priority scheduling (usually rate-monotonic scheduling).
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] With fixed priorities, it is easy to predict that overload conditions will cause the low-priority processes to miss deadlines, while the highest-priority process will still meet its deadline.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] There is a significant body of research dealing with EDF scheduling in real-time computing; it is possible to calculate worst case response times of processes in EDF, to deal with other types of processes than periodic processes and to use servers to regulate overloads.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Consider 3 periodic processes scheduled on a preemptive uniprocessor.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] In this example, the units of time may be considered to be schedulable time slices.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] The deadlines are that each periodic process must complete within its period.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] In the timing diagram, the columns represent time slices with time increasing to the right, and the processes all start their periods at time slice 0.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] The timing diagram's alternating blue and white shading indicates each process's periods, with deadlines at the color changes.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] The first process scheduled by EDF is P2, because its period is shortest, and therefore it has the earliest deadline.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Likewise, when P2 completes, P1 is scheduled, followed by P3.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] At time slice 5, both P2 and P3 have the same deadline, needing to complete before time slice 10, so EDF may schedule either one.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Since the least common multiple of the periods is 40, the scheduling pattern can repeat every 40 time slices.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] But, only 37 of those 40 time slices are used by P1, P2, or P3.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Since the utilization, 92.5%, is not greater than 100%, the system is schedulable with EDF.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Undesirable deadline interchanges may occur with EDF scheduling.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] A process may use a shared resource inside a critical section, to prevent it from being pre-emptively descheduled in favour of another process with an earlier deadline.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] If so, it becomes important for the scheduler to assign the running process the earliest deadline from among the other processes waiting for the resource.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Otherwise the processes with earlier deadlines might miss them.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] This is especially important if the process running the critical section has a much longer time to complete and exit from its critical section, which will delay releasing the shared resource.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] But the process might still be pre-empted in favour of others that have earlier deadlines but do not share the critical resource.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] This hazard of deadline interchange is analogous to priority inversion when using fixed-priority pre-emptive scheduling.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] To speed up the deadline search within the ready queue, the queue entries be sorted according to their deadlines.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] When a new process or a periodic process is given a new deadline, it is inserted before the first process with a later deadline.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] This way, the processes with the earliest deadlines are always at the beginning of the queue.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] In a heavy-traffic analysis of the behavior of a single-server queue under an earliest-deadline-first scheduling policy with reneging, the processes have deadlines and are served only until their deadlines elapse.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] The fraction of "reneged work", defined as the residual work not serviced due to elapsed deadlines, is an important performance measure.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] It is commonly accepted that an implementation of fixed-priority pre-emptive scheduling (FPS) is simpler than a dynamic priority scheduler, like the EDF.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] However, when comparing the maximum usage of an optimal scheduling under fixed priority (with the priority of each thread given by the rate-monotonic scheduling), the EDF can reach 100% while the theoretical maximum value for rate-monotonic scheduling is around 69%.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] In practical cases, such as embedded systems using a fixed, 32-bit representation of time, scheduling decisions can be made using this implementation in a small fixed-constant time which is independent of the number of system tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] In such situations experiments have found little discernible difference in overhead between the EDF and FPS, even for task sets of (comparatively) large cardinality.
[src:real-time-systems/earliest-deadline-first-scheduling] Note that EDF does not make any specific assumption on the periodicity of the tasks; hence, it can be used for scheduling periodic as well as aperiodic tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] In computing, **interrupt latency** refers to the delay between the start of an Interrupt Request (IRQ) and the start of the respective Interrupt Service Routine (ISR).
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] For many operating systems, devices are serviced as soon as the device's interrupt handler is executed.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Interrupt latency may be affected by microprocessor design, interrupt controllers, interrupt masking, and the operating system's (OS) interrupt handling methods.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] There is usually a trade-off between interrupt latency, throughput, and processor utilization.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Many of the techniques of CPU and OS design that improve interrupt latency will decrease throughput and increase processor utilization.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Techniques that increase throughput may increase interrupt latency and increase processor utilization.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Lastly, trying to reduce processor utilization may increase interrupt latency and decrease throughput.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Minimum interrupt latency is largely determined by the interrupt controller circuit and its configuration.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] They can also affect the jitter in the interrupt latency, which can drastically affect the real-time schedulability of the system.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] The Intel APIC architecture is well known for producing a huge amount of interrupt latency jitter.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Maximum interrupt latency is largely determined by the methods an OS uses for interrupt handling.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] For example, most processors allow programs to disable interrupts, putting off the execution of interrupt handlers, in order to protect critical sections of code.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] During the execution of such a critical section, all interrupt handlers that cannot execute safely within a critical section are blocked (they save the minimum amount of information required to restart the interrupt handler after all critical sections have exited).
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] So the interrupt latency for a blocked interrupt is extended to the end of the critical section, plus any interrupts with equal and higher priority that arrived while the block was in place.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Many computer systems require low interrupt latencies, especially embedded systems that need to control machinery in real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Sometimes these systems use a real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] An RTOS makes the promise that no more than a specified maximum amount of time will pass between executions of subroutines.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] In order to do this, the RTOS must also guarantee that interrupt latency will never exceed a predefined maximum.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Advanced interrupt controllers implement a multitude of hardware features in order to minimize the overhead during context switches and the effective interrupt latency.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Also, there are many other methods hardware may use to help lower the requirements for shorter interrupt latency in order to make a given interrupt latency tolerable in a situation.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] These include buffers, and flow control.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] For example, most network cards implement transmit and receive ring buffers, interrupt rate limiting, and hardware flow control.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Buffers allow data to be stored until it can be transferred, and flow control allows the network card to pause communications without having to discard data if the buffer is full.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Modern hardware also implements interrupt rate limiting.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] This helps prevent interrupt storms or live-locks by having the hardware wait a programmable minimum amount of time between each interrupt it generates.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Interrupt rate limiting reduces the amount of time spent servicing interrupts, allowing the processor to spend more time doing useful work.
[src:real-time-systems/interrupt-latency] Exceeding this time results in a soft (recoverable) or hard (non-recoverable) error.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In electronics and telecommunications, **jitter** is the deviation from true periodicity of a presumably periodic signal, often in relation to a reference clock signal.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In clock recovery applications it is called **timing jitter**.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter is a significant, and usually undesired, factor in the design of almost all communications links.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter can be quantified in the same terms as all time-varying signals, e.g., root mean square (RMS), or peak-to-peak displacement.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Also, like other time-varying signals, jitter can be expressed in terms of spectral density.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter may be caused by electromagnetic interference and crosstalk with carriers of other signals.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter can cause a display monitor to flicker, affect the performance of processors in personal computers, introduce clicks or other undesired effects in audio signals, and cause loss of transmitted data between network devices.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The amount of tolerable jitter depends on the affected application.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] in the position of a clock's edge from where it would ideally be.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Maximum error committed by a clock under test in measuring a time interval for a given period of time.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The difference between any one clock period and the ideal or average clock period.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Hence, synchronous circuitry benefits from minimizing period jitter, so that the shortest clock period approaches the average clock period.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The difference in duration of any two adjacent clock periods.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In telecommunications, the unit used for the above types of jitter is usually the unit interval (UI) which quantifies the jitter in terms of a fraction of the transmission unit period.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] This unit is useful because it scales with clock frequency and thus allows relatively slow interconnects such as T1 to be compared to higher-speed internet backbone links such as OC-192.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Absolute units such as *picoseconds* are more common in microprocessor applications.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Units of *degrees* and *radians* are also used.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] If jitter has a Gaussian distribution, it is usually quantified using the standard deviation of this distribution.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] This translates to an RMS measurement for a zero-mean distribution.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Often, jitter distribution is significantly non-Gaussian.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] This can occur if the jitter is caused by external sources such as power supply noise.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In these cases, *peak-to-peak* measurements may be more useful.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Many efforts have been made to meaningfully quantify distributions that are neither Gaussian nor have a meaningful peak level.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] All have shortcomings but most tend to be good enough for the purposes of engineering work.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In computer networking, *jitter* can refer to packet delay variation, the variation (statistical dispersion) in the delay of the packets.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] One of the main differences between random and deterministic jitter is that deterministic jitter is bounded and random jitter is unbounded.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Random jitter, also called Gaussian jitter, is unpredictable electronic timing noise.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Random jitter typically follows a normal distribution due to being caused by thermal noise in an electrical circuit.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] in which the value of *n* is based on the BER required of the link.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A common BER used in communication standards such as Ethernet is 10−12.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog conversion of signals, the sampling is normally assumed to be periodic with a fixed period—the time between every two samples is the same.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] If there is jitter present on the clock signal to the analog-to-digital converter or a digital-to-analog converter, the time between samples varies and instantaneous signal error arises.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The error is proportional to the slew rate of the desired signal and the absolute value of the clock error.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The effect of jitter on the signal depends on the nature of the jitter.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Random jitter tends to add broadband noise while deterministic jitter tends to add errant spectral components, *birdys*.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In some conditions, less than a nanosecond of jitter can reduce the effective bit resolution of a converter with a Nyquist frequency of 22 kHz to 14 bits.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Sampling jitter is an important consideration in high-frequency signal conversion, or where the clock signal is especially prone to interference.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In digital antenna arrays ADC and DAC jitters are the important factors determining the direction of arrival estimation accuracy and the depth of jammers suppression.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In the context of computer networks, packet jitter or packet delay variation (PDV) is the variation in latency as measured in the variability over time of the end-to-end delay across a network.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A network with constant delay has no packet jitter.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Packet jitter is expressed as an average of the deviation from the network mean delay.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] PDV is an important quality of service factor in assessment of network performance.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Transmitting a burst of traffic at a high rate followed by an interval or period of lower or zero rate transmission may also be seen as a form of jitter, as it represents a deviation from the average transmission rate.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] However, unlike the jitter caused by variation in latency, transmitting in bursts may be seen as a desirable feature, e.g. in variable bitrate transmissions.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Video or image jitter occurs when the horizontal lines of video image frames are randomly displaced due to the corruption of synchronization signals or electromagnetic interference during video transmission.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A model-based dejittering study has been carried out under the framework of digital image and video restoration.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter in serial bus architectures is measured by means of eye patterns.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] There are standards for jitter measurement in serial bus architectures.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The standards cover jitter tolerance, jitter transfer function and jitter generation, with the required values for these attributes varying among different applications.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Where applicable, compliant systems are required to conform to these standards.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Testing for jitter and its measurement is of growing importance to electronics engineers because of increased clock frequencies in digital electronic circuitry to achieve higher device performance.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Higher clock frequencies have commensurately smaller eye openings and thus impose tighter tolerances on jitter.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] For example, modern computer motherboards have serial bus architectures with eye openings of 160 picoseconds or less.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] This is extremely small compared to parallel bus architectures with equivalent performance, which may have eye openings on the order of 1000 picoseconds.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter is measured and evaluated in various ways depending on the type of circuit under test.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In all cases, the goal of jitter measurement is to verify that the jitter will not disrupt normal operation of the circuit.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Testing of device performance for jitter tolerance may involve injection of jitter into electronic components with specialized test equipment.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A less direct approach—in which analog waveforms are digitized and the resulting data stream analyzed—is employed when measuring pixel jitter in frame grabbers.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Anti-jitter circuits (AJCs) are a class of electronic circuits designed to reduce the level of jitter in a clock signal.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] AJCs operate by re-timing the output pulses so they align more closely to an idealized clock.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] They are widely used in clock and data recovery circuits in digital communications, as well as for data sampling systems such as the analog-to-digital converter and digital-to-analog converter.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Examples of anti-jitter circuits include phase-locked loop and delay-locked loop.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Jitter buffers or de-jitter buffers are buffers used to counter jitter introduced by queuing in packet-switched networks to ensure continuous playout of an audio or video media stream transmitted over the network.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The maximum jitter that can be countered by a de-jitter buffer is equal to the buffering delay introduced before starting the play-out of the media stream.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] In the context of packet-switched networks, the term *packet delay variation* is often preferred over *jitter*.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Some systems use sophisticated delay-optimal de-jitter buffers that are capable of adapting the buffering delay to changing network characteristics.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] The adaptation logic is based on the jitter estimates computed from the arrival characteristics of the media packets.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Adjustments associated with adaptive de-jittering involve introducing discontinuities in the media play-out, which may be noticeable to the listener or viewer.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] Adaptive de-jittering is usually carried out for audio play-outs that include voice activity detection, which allows the lengths of the silence periods to be adjusted, thus minimizing the perceptual impact of the adaptation.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer is a device that reduces jitter in a digital signal.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer usually consists of an elastic buffer in which the signal is temporarily stored and then retransmitted at a rate based on the average rate of the incoming signal.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer may not be effective in removing low-frequency jitter (wander).
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A filter can be designed to minimize the effect of sampling jitter.
[src:real-time-systems/jitter] A jitter signal can be decomposed into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs), which can be further applied for filtering or dejittering.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In computing, **preemption** is the act performed by an external scheduler — without assistance or cooperation from the task — of temporarily interrupting an executing task, with the intention of resuming it at a later time.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] This preemptive scheduler usually runs in the most privileged protection ring, meaning that interruption and then resumption are considered highly secure actions.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Such changes to the currently executing task of a processor are known as context switching.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In any given system design, some operations performed by the system may not be preemptable.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] This usually applies to kernel functions and service interrupts which, if not permitted to run to completion, would tend to produce race conditions resulting in deadlock.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Barring the scheduler from preempting tasks while they are processing kernel functions simplifies the kernel design at the expense of system responsiveness.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The distinction between user mode and kernel mode, which determines privilege level within the system, may also be used to distinguish whether a task is currently preemptable.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Most modern operating systems have **preemptive kernels**, which are designed to permit tasks to be preempted even when in kernel mode.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Examples of such operating systems are Solaris 2.0/SunOS 5.0, Windows NT, Linux kernel (2.5.4 and newer), AIX and some BSD systems (NetBSD, since version 5).
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The term **preemptive multitasking** is used to distinguish a multitasking operating system, which permits preemption of tasks, from a cooperative multitasking system wherein processes or tasks must be explicitly programmed to yield when they do not need system resources.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In simple terms: Preemptive multitasking involves the use of an interrupt mechanism which suspends the currently executing process and invokes a scheduler to determine which process should execute next.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Therefore, all processes will get some amount of CPU time at any given time.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In preemptive multitasking, the operating system kernel can also initiate a context switch to satisfy the scheduling policy's priority constraint, thus preempting the active task.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In general, preemption means "prior seizure of".
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] When the high-priority task at that instance seizes the currently running task, it is known as preemptive scheduling.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The term "preemptive multitasking" is sometimes mistakenly used when the intended meaning is more specific, referring instead to the class of scheduling policies known as *time-shared scheduling*, or *time-sharing*.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking allows the computer system to more reliably guarantee each process a regular "slice" of operating time.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] It also allows the system to rapidly deal with important external events like incoming data, which might require the immediate attention of one or another process.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] At any specific time, processes can be grouped into two categories: those that are waiting for input or output (called "I/O bound"), and those that are fully utilizing the CPU ("CPU bound").
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In early systems, processes would often "poll" or "busy-wait" while waiting for requested input (such as disk, keyboard or network input).
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] During this time, the process was not performing useful work, but still maintained complete control of the CPU.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] With the advent of interrupts and preemptive multitasking, these I/O bound processes could be "blocked", or put on hold, pending the arrival of the necessary data, allowing other processes to utilize the CPU.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] As the arrival of the requested data would generate an interrupt, blocked processes could be guaranteed a timely return to execution.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Although multitasking techniques were originally developed to allow multiple users to share a single machine, it became apparent that multitasking was useful regardless of the number of users.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Many operating systems, from mainframes down to single-user personal computers and no-user control systems (like those in robotic spacecraft), have recognized the usefulness of multitasking support for a variety of reasons.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Multitasking makes it possible for a single user to run multiple applications at the same time, or to run "background" processes while retaining control of the computer.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The period of time for which a process is allowed to run in a preemptive multitasking system is generally called the *time slice* or *quantum*.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The scheduler is run once every time slice to choose the next process to run.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The length of each time slice can be critical to balancing system performance vs process responsiveness - if the time slice is too short then the scheduler itself will consume too much processing time, but if the time slice is too long, processes will take longer to respond to input.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] An interrupt is scheduled to allow the operating system kernel to switch between processes when their time slices expire, effectively allowing the processor's time to be shared among a number of tasks, giving the illusion that it is dealing with these tasks in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The operating system which controls such a design is called a multi-tasking system.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Today, nearly all operating systems support preemptive multitasking, including the current versions of Windows, Linux (including Android), and Darwin (including macOS and iOS).
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Sinclair QDOS and AmigaOS on the Amiga were also microcomputer operating systems offering preemptive multitasking as a core feature.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] These both ran on Motorola 68000-family microprocessors without memory management.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Amiga OS used dynamic loading of relocatable code blocks ("hunks" in Amiga jargon) to multitask preemptively all processes in the same flat address space.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Early operating systems for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS and PC DOS, did not support multitasking at all, however alternative operating systems such as MP/M-86 (1981) and Concurrent CP/M-86 did support preemptive multitasking.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Other Unix-like systems including MINIX and Coherent provided preemptive multitasking on 1980s-era personal computers.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Later MS-DOS compatible systems natively supporting preemptive multitasking/multithreading include Concurrent DOS, Multiuser DOS, Novell DOS (later called Caldera OpenDOS and DR-DOS 7.02 and higher).
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Since Concurrent DOS 386, they could also run multiple DOS programs concurrently in virtual DOS machines.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] The earliest version of Windows to support a limited form of preemptive multitasking was Windows/386 2.0, which used the Intel 80386's Virtual 8086 mode to run DOS applications in virtual 8086 machines, commonly known as "DOS boxes", which could be preempted.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In Windows 95, 98 and Me, 32-bit applications were made preemptive by running each one in a separate address space, but 16-bit applications remained cooperative for backward compatibility.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] In Windows 3.1x (protected mode), the kernel and virtual device drivers ran preemptively, but all 16-bit applications were non-preemptive and shared the same address space.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Preemptive multitasking has always been supported by Windows NT (all versions), OS/2 (native applications), Unix and Unix-like systems (such as Linux, BSD and macOS), VMS, OS/360, and many other operating systems designed for use in the academic and medium-to-large business markets.
[src:real-time-systems/preemption-computing] Early versions of the classic Mac OS did not support multitasking at all, with cooperative multitasking becoming available via MultiFinder in System Software 5 and then standard in System 7.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] In computer science, **priority inversion** is a scenario in scheduling in which a high-priority task is indirectly superseded by a lower-priority task, effectively inverting the assigned priorities of the tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] This violates the priority model that every task can only be prevented from running by a higher-priority task.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Inversion occurs when there is a resource contention with a (low-priority) task that is then preempted by a higher-priority task.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Consider two tasks *H* and *L*, of high and low priority, respectively, either of which can acquire exclusive use of a shared resource *R*.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] If *H* attempts to acquire *R* after *L* has acquired it, then *H* becomes blocked until *L* relinquishes the resource.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Sharing an exclusive-use resource (*R* in this case) in a well-designed system typically involves *L* relinquishing *R* promptly so that *H* (a higher-priority task) does not stay blocked for excessive periods of time.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Despite good design, however, it is possible that a third task *M* of medium priority becomes runnable during *L*'s use of *R*.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] In some cases, priority inversion can occur without causing immediate harm—the delayed execution of the high-priority task goes unnoticed, and eventually, the low-priority task releases the shared resource.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] However, there are also many situations in which priority inversion can cause serious problems.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] If the high-priority task is left starved of the resources, it might lead to a system malfunction or the triggering of pre-defined corrective measures, such as a watchdog timer resetting the entire system.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] The trouble experienced by the Mars Pathfinder lander in 1997 is a classic example of problems caused by priority inversion in realtime systems.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Priority inversion can also reduce the perceived performance of the system.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Low-priority tasks usually have a low priority because it is not important for them to finish promptly (for example, they might be a batch job or another non-interactive activity).
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Similarly, a high-priority task has a high priority because it is more likely to be subject to strict time constraints—it may be providing data to an interactive user, or acting subject to real-time response guarantees.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Because priority inversion results in the execution of a lower-priority task blocking the high-priority task, it can lead to reduced system responsiveness or even the violation of response time guarantees.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] A similar problem called deadline interchange can occur within earliest deadline first scheduling (EDF).
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] The existence of this problem has been known since the 1970s.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Lampson and Redell published one of the first papers to point out the priority inversion problem.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Systems such as the UNIX kernel were already addressing the problem with the splx() primitive.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] There is no foolproof method to predict the situation.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] With no third priority, inversion is impossible.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Since there's only one piece of lock data (the interrupt-enable bit), misordering locking is impossible, and so deadlocks cannot occur.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Since the critical regions always run to completion, hangs do not occur.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Note that this only works if all interrupts are disabled.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] If only a particular hardware device's interrupt is disabled, priority inversion is reintroduced by the hardware's prioritization of interrupts.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] In early versions of UNIX, a series of primitives named splx(0) ... splx(7) disabled all interrupts up through the given priority.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] By properly choosing the highest priority of any interrupt that ever entered the critical section, the priority inversion problem could be solved without locking out all of the interrupts.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] order, i.e. the slower devices had lower priorities.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Interprocessor communications are expensive and slow on most multiple-CPU systems.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Therefore, most such systems are designed to minimize shared resources.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] As a result, this scheme actually works well on many practical systems.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] , where they are prized for their reliability, simplicity and low resource use.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] These schemes also require clever programming to keep the critical sections very brief.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Many software engineers consider them impractical in general-purpose computers.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] process (that runs the operating system code) has a characteristic (high) priority of its own, which is assigned to the task of locking the mutex.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] This works well, provided the other high-priority task(s) that try to access the mutex do not have a priority higher than the ceiling priority.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] Once the resource is released, the low-priority task continues at its original priority level.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] in priority until they exit the critical section.
[src:real-time-systems/priority-inversion] until it was replaced by AutoBoost a form of priority inheritance.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In computer science, **rate-monotonic scheduling** (**RMS**) is a priority assignment algorithm used in real-time operating systems (RTOS) with a static-priority scheduling class.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] The static priorities are assigned according to the cycle duration of the job, so a shorter cycle duration results in a higher job priority.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] These operating systems are generally preemptive and have deterministic guarantees with regard to response times.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Rate monotonic analysis is used in conjunction with those systems to provide scheduling guarantees for a particular application.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] It is a mathematical model that contains a calculated simulation of periods in a closed system, where round-robin and time-sharing schedulers fail to meet the scheduling needs otherwise.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Rate monotonic scheduling looks at a run modeling of all threads in the system and determines how much time is needed to meet the guarantees for the set of threads in question.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] The rate-monotonic priority assignment is *optimal* under the given assumptions, meaning that if any static-priority scheduling algorithm can meet all the deadlines, then the rate-monotonic algorithm can too.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] The deadline-monotonic scheduling algorithm is also optimal with equal periods and deadlines, in fact in this case the algorithms are identical; in addition, deadline monotonic scheduling is optimal when deadlines are less than periods.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] For the task model in which deadlines can be greater than periods, Audsley's algorithm endowed with an exact schedulability test for this model finds an optimal priority assignment.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Liu & Layland (1973) proved that for a set of n periodic tasks with unique periods, a feasible schedule that will always meet deadlines exists if the CPU utilization is below a specific bound (depending on the number of tasks).
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] where U is the utilization factor, Ci is the computation time for process i, Ti is the release period (with deadline one period later) for process i, and n is the number of processes to be scheduled.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] For example, U ≤ 0.8284 for two processes.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Therefore, a rough estimate when ${n}\geq {10}$ is that RMS can meet all of the deadlines if total CPU utilization, U, is less than 70%.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] The other 30% of the CPU can be dedicated to lower-priority, non-real-time tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] For smaller values of n or in cases where U is close to this estimate, the calculated utilization bound should be used.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In practice, for the ${i^{th}}$ process, ${C_{i}}$ should represent the worst-case (i.e. longest) computation time and ${T_{i}}$ should represent the worst-case deadline (i.e. shortest period) in which all processing must occur.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In queueing theory, Ti is called the **interarrival time**, and Ci is called the **service time**.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] It is acknowledged by Liu and Layland that it is not always feasible to have a harmonic task set and that in practice other mitigation measures, such as buffering for tasks with soft-time deadlines or using a dynamic priority assignment approach may be used instead to allow for a higher bound.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] When ${K}{=}{1}$ , the upper bound becomes 1.0, representing full utilization.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] where Ui is the CPU utilization for each task.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] It is the tightest upper bound that can be found using only the individual task utilization factors.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In many practical applications, resources are shared and the unmodified **RMS** will be subject to priority inversion and deadlock hazards.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In practice, this is solved by disabling preemption or by priority inheritance.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Alternative methods are to use lock-free algorithms or avoid the sharing of a mutex/semaphore across threads with different priorities.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] This is so that resource conflicts cannot result in the first place.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Priority inheritance algorithms can be characterized by two parameters.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] First, is the inheritance lazy (only when essential) or immediate (boost priority before there is a conflict).
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] In practice there is no mathematical difference (in terms of the Liu-Layland system utilization bound) between the lazy and immediate algorithms, and the immediate algorithms are more efficient to implement, and so they are the ones used by most practical systems.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] An example of usage of basic priority inheritance is related to the "Mars Pathfinder reset bug" which was fixed on Mars by changing the creation flags for the semaphore so as to enable the priority inheritance.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] All interrupt service routines (ISRs), whether they have a hard real-time deadline or not should be included in RMS analysis to determine schedulability in cases where ISRs have priorities above all scheduler-controlled tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] An ISR may already be appropriately prioritized under RMS rules if its processing period is shorter than that of the shortest, non-ISR process.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] However, an ISR with a period/deadline longer than any non-ISR process period with a critical deadline results in a violation of RMS and prevents the use of the calculated bounds for determining schedulability of a task set.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] One method for mitigating a mis-prioritized ISR is to adjust the analysis by reducing the ISR's period to be equal to that of the shortest period, if possible.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Imposing this shorter period results in prioritization that conforms to RMS, but also results in a higher utilization factor for the ISR and therefore for the total utilization factor, which may still be below the allowable bound and therefore schedulability can be proven.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] As an example, consider a hardware ISR that has a computation time, ${C_{isr}}$ of 500 microseconds and a period, ${T_{isr}}$ , of 4 milliseconds.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] If the shortest scheduler-controlled task has a period, ${T_{1}}$ of 1 millisecond, then the ISR would have a higher priority, but a lower rate, which violates RMS.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] For the purposes of proving schedulability, set ${T_{isr}}={T_{1}}$ and recalculate the utilization factor for the ISR (which also raises the total utilization factor).
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] This utilization factor would be used when adding up the total utilization factor for the task set and comparing to the upper bound to prove schedulability.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] It should be emphasized that adjusting the period of the ISR is for analysis only and that the true period of the ISR remains unchanged.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Another method for mitigating a mis-prioritized ISR is to use the ISR to only set a new semaphore/mutex while moving the time-intensive processing to a new process that has been appropriately prioritized using RMS and will block on the new semaphore/mutex.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] When determining schedulability, a margin of CPU utilization due to ISR activity should be subtracted from the least upper bound.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] ISRs with negligible utilization may be ignored.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Under RMS, P2 has the highest release rate (i.e. the shortest release period) and so would have the highest priority, followed by P1 and finally P3.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Because $U<U_{lub}$ , and because being below the Least Upper Bound is a sufficient condition, the system is guaranteed to be schedulable.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Under RMS, P2 has the highest release rate (i.e. the shortest release period) and so would have the highest priority, followed by P3 and finally P1.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Since $U>U_{lub}$ , the system is determined *not* to be guaranteed to be schedulable by the Liu and Layland bound.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] it is found that the task set *is* schedulable.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Under RMS, P2 has the highest rate (i.e. the shortest period) and so would have the highest priority, followed by P3 and finally P1.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Since $2.0{<}2.0475$ the system is determined to *not* be guaranteed to be schedulable by the Hyperbolic bound.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Because ${T_{3}}={2{T_{2}}}$ , tasks 2 and 3 can be considered a harmonic task subset.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Task 1 forms its own harmonic task subset.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Therefore, the number of harmonic task subsets, K, is 2.
[src:real-time-systems/rate-monotonic-scheduling] Using the total utilization factor calculated above (0.81875), since $0.81875<0.828$ the system is determined to be schedulable.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:real-time-systems/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:real-time-systems/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Because they have highly deterministic timing behavior, TT systems have been used for many years to develop safety-critical aerospace and related systems.
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] An early text that sets forth the principles of time triggered architecture, communications, and sparse time approaches is *Real-Time Systems: Design Principles for Distributed Embedded Applications* in 1997.
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Use of TT systems was popularized by the publication of *Patterns for Time-Triggered Embedded Systems* (PTTES) in 2001 and the related introductory book *Embedded C* in 2002.
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] The PTTES book also introduced the concepts of time-triggered hybrid schedulers (an architecture for time-triggered systems that require task pre-emption) and shared-clock schedulers (an architecture for distributed time-triggered systems involving multiple, synchronized, nodes).
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Since publication of PTTES, extensive research work on TT systems has been carried out.
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Time-triggered systems are now commonly associated with international safety standards such as IEC 61508 (industrial systems), ISO 26262 (automotive systems), IEC 62304 (medical systems) and IEC 60730 (household goods).
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Time-triggered systems can be viewed as a subset of a more general event-triggered (ET) system architecture (see event-driven programming).
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] Implementation of an ET system will typically involve use of multiple interrupts, each associated with specific periodic events (such as timer overflows) or aperiodic events (such as the arrival of messages over a communication bus at random points in time).
[src:real-time-systems/time-triggered-architecture] ET designs are traditionally associated with the use of what is known as a real-time operating system (or RTOS), though use of such a software platform is not a defining characteristic of an ET architecture.
